</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The term <i>inflammatory bowel disease</i> (IBD) is used to describe multiple idiopathic disorders of the gastrointestinal tract. As many as one-quarter of patients with IBD initially present in childhood or adolescence. Multiple methods can be used to diagnose IBD in this age group, including computed tomographic (CT) enterography, magnetic resonance (MR) enterography, small bowel follow-through examination, ileocolonoscopy, and capsule endoscopy. However, CT enterography and MR enterography have become the imaging modalities of choice due to their exquisite image quality, rapid acquisition time, lack of need for bowel preparation, and ability to help diagnose the extraintestinal complications of IBD. In addition to being radiation free, MR enterography can help evaluate peristalsis, has high contrast resolution, and allows the use of diffusion-weighted imaging. The authors discuss the use of CT enterography and MR enterography in the context of pediatric IBD in terms of advantages and disadvantages, protocol, and imaging findings.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.337105140">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.337105140">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig1a.jpeg" height="768" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Bowel wall thickening. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows multiple areas of bowel wall thickening throughout the abdomen (arrows). Each thickened bowel segment demonstrates mucosal hyperenhancement, mural stratification, and engorged vasa recta. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed bSSFP MR enterographic image in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows bowel wall thickening of the descending colon (white arrow) and wispy increased T2 signal intensity in the surrounding pericolonic fat (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig1b.jpeg" height="768" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Bowel wall thickening. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows multiple areas of bowel wall thickening throughout the abdomen (arrows). Each thickened bowel segment demonstrates mucosal hyperenhancement, mural stratification, and engorged vasa recta. <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed bSSFP MR enterographic image in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows bowel wall thickening of the descending colon (white arrow) and wispy increased T2 signal intensity in the surrounding pericolonic fat (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig2a.jpeg" height="751" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Mucosal hyperenhancement. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows multiple segments of small bowel in which the mucosa enhances to a greater degree than in other nearby segments (arrows). At each affected segment, there is also bowel wall thickening and mural stratification. The jejunum and nondistended loops of bowel are seen to mimic mucosal hyperenhancement (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 12-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows discontinuous regions of bowel wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig2b.jpeg" height="751" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Mucosal hyperenhancement. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows multiple segments of small bowel in which the mucosa enhances to a greater degree than in other nearby segments (arrows). At each affected segment, there is also bowel wall thickening and mural stratification. The jejunum and nondistended loops of bowel are seen to mimic mucosal hyperenhancement (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 12-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows discontinuous regions of bowel wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig3.jpeg" height="769" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Coronal diffusion-weighted image with background body suppression in an 18-year-old man with Crohn disease shows an S-shaped area of restricted diffusion corresponding to the terminal ileum (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig4a.jpeg" height="838" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Mural stratification. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows a focal segment of small bowel with mural stratification (arrows). In this segment, the mucosa is thickened and hyperenhancing (arrowhead), and the bowel wall is thickened and has fluid attenuation. The segment also displays luminal narrowing and engorged vasa recta. <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows mural stratification and mucosal hyperenhancement of a small bowel loop in the left lower quadrant (white arrow). The vasa recta supplying this inflamed bowel loop are engorged (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig4b.jpeg" height="838" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Mural stratification. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows a focal segment of small bowel with mural stratification (arrows). In this segment, the mucosa is thickened and hyperenhancing (arrowhead), and the bowel wall is thickened and has fluid attenuation. The segment also displays luminal narrowing and engorged vasa recta. <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 20 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows mural stratification and mucosal hyperenhancement of a small bowel loop in the left lower quadrant (white arrow). The vasa recta supplying this inflamed bowel loop are engorged (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig5a.jpeg" height="700" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Skip lesions. Axial CT enterographic images of the pelvis in a 17-year-old girl with Crohn disease show two separate segments of bowel with mucosal hyperenhancement and bowel wall thickening (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig5b.jpeg" height="700" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Skip lesions. Axial CT enterographic images of the pelvis in a 17-year-old girl with Crohn disease show two separate segments of bowel with mucosal hyperenhancement and bowel wall thickening (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig6a.jpeg" height="683" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Luminal narrowing. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows narrowing of the lumen of the terminal ileum (white arrow). The proximal bowel (not shown) was not dilated, and there were no other signs of obstruction. Note the multiple areas of mucosal hyperenhancement, mural stratification, and bowel wall thickening, particularly in the left side of the abdomen (black arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration shows mucosal hyperenhancement, bowel wall thickening, and luminal narrowing of the terminal ileum (arrow). The more proximal terminal ileum is not dilated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig6b.jpeg" height="683" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Luminal narrowing. <b>(a)</b> Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows narrowing of the lumen of the terminal ileum (white arrow). The proximal bowel (not shown) was not dilated, and there were no other signs of obstruction. Note the multiple areas of mucosal hyperenhancement, mural stratification, and bowel wall thickening, particularly in the left side of the abdomen (black arrows). <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration shows mucosal hyperenhancement, bowel wall thickening, and luminal narrowing of the terminal ileum (arrow). The more proximal terminal ileum is not dilated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig7a.jpeg" height="775" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Strictures. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the pelvis in the same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Figure 6</a> shows a long-segment stricture of the terminal ileum (arrows). Note the bright ovoid area (arrowhead), which represents a pill lodged in the proximal portion of the stricture. The bowel proximal to the stricture is dilated and filled with air. In addition to the stricture, there is pericolonic fat stranding and free fluid within the pelvis. <b>(b)</b> Axial LAVA image obtained 120 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows a 5.5-cm strictured segment of small bowel (white arrow). The small bowel proximal to this segment is dilated (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig7b.jpeg" height="775" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Strictures. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the pelvis in the same patient as in <a href="#fig6a">Figure 6</a> shows a long-segment stricture of the terminal ileum (arrows). Note the bright ovoid area (arrowhead), which represents a pill lodged in the proximal portion of the stricture. The bowel proximal to the stricture is dilated and filled with air. In addition to the stricture, there is pericolonic fat stranding and free fluid within the pelvis. <b>(b)</b> Axial LAVA image obtained 120 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows a 5.5-cm strictured segment of small bowel (white arrow). The small bowel proximal to this segment is dilated (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig8a.jpeg" height="755" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Fistulas. <b>(a)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration in an 18-year-old man with Crohn disease shows multiple loops of the small bowel and colon matted together and tethered at a focal point (arrowhead). This point of fistulous connection appears similar to an asterisk. The focal point is composed of multiple fistulas, including an interloop fistula (black arrow) and an ileocolic fistula (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial LAVA image obtained 120 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 16-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows a fistula between the colon and uterus (white arrow). A short-segment stricture (arrowhead) is seen just proximal to the fistula. The small bowel upstream from the stricture is dilated, and there is fecalization of the small bowel contents (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig8b.jpeg" height="755" width="836" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Fistulas. <b>(a)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration in an 18-year-old man with Crohn disease shows multiple loops of the small bowel and colon matted together and tethered at a focal point (arrowhead). This point of fistulous connection appears similar to an asterisk. The focal point is composed of multiple fistulas, including an interloop fistula (black arrow) and an ileocolic fistula (white arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial LAVA image obtained 120 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 16-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows a fistula between the colon and uterus (white arrow). A short-segment stricture (arrowhead) is seen just proximal to the fistula. The small bowel upstream from the stricture is dilated, and there is fecalization of the small bowel contents (black arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig9a.jpeg" height="741" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Comb sign. <b>(a)</b> Oblique coronal maximum intensity projection CT enterographic image of the pelvis in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows abnormal bowel wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement of the terminal ileum. The vasa recta are engorged (arrows) and, together with an inflamed terminal ileum, create the comb sign. <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows engorged vasa recta (arrows) producing the comb sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig9b.jpeg" height="741" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Comb sign. <b>(a)</b> Oblique coronal maximum intensity projection CT enterographic image of the pelvis in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows abnormal bowel wall thickening and mucosal hyperenhancement of the terminal ileum. The vasa recta are engorged (arrows) and, together with an inflamed terminal ileum, create the comb sign. <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 60 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows engorged vasa recta (arrows) producing the comb sign.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig10.jpeg" height="756" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Engorged vasa recta coursing perpendicular to the imaging plane. Axial CT enterographic image in a 16-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows the vasa recta to be increased in size and number, giving the appearance of multiple dots (arrows). Segments of bowel with mucosal hyperenhancement, mural stratification, and bowel wall thickening are also seen.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig11a.jpeg" height="778" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Fat stranding. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the pelvis in a 21-year-old woman shows mucosal hyperenhancement, mural thickening, and mural stratification of the cecum. In addition, there is stranding within the pericecal fat (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial LAVA image obtained 120 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 19-year-old woman with Crohn disease shows mucosal hyperenhancement and bowel wall thickening of the ileum and ileostomy. Stranding within the adjacent mesenteric fat (arrow) is also noted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig11b.jpeg" height="778" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Fat stranding. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the pelvis in a 21-year-old woman shows mucosal hyperenhancement, mural thickening, and mural stratification of the cecum. In addition, there is stranding within the pericecal fat (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial LAVA image obtained 120 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 19-year-old woman with Crohn disease shows mucosal hyperenhancement and bowel wall thickening of the ileum and ileostomy. Stranding within the adjacent mesenteric fat (arrow) is also noted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig12.jpeg" height="761" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span> Prominent lymph nodes. Coronal CT enterographic image of the abdomen in a pediatric patient with Crohn disease shows multiple mesenteric lymph nodes (arrows). Although these lymph nodes are no more than 1 cm in the short axis, they are larger and more numerous than what is typically seen in children.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig13a.jpeg" height="747" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Abscesses. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the pelvis in an 18-year-old woman with Crohn disease shows an irregular loculated collection in the perirectal region with wall thickening and enhancement (arrows), findings consistent with an abscess. A small locule of gas is present within the collection (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 180 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows a pelvic abscess with a thickened and enhancing wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig13b.jpeg" height="747" width="837" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Abscesses. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT enterographic image of the pelvis in an 18-year-old woman with Crohn disease shows an irregular loculated collection in the perirectal region with wall thickening and enhancement (arrows), findings consistent with an abscess. A small locule of gas is present within the collection (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Coronal LAVA image obtained 180 seconds after contrast agent administration in a 15-year-old boy with Crohn disease shows a pelvic abscess with a thickened and enhancing wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig14.jpeg" height="760" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Free fluid. Axial fat-saturated bSSFP image in a 15-year-old girl with Crohn disease shows free fluid within the pelvis (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig15.jpeg" height="745" width="842" aria-labelledby="fig15" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15</span> Gallstone. Axial CT enterographic image of the gallbladder in an 18-year-old woman with Crohn disease shows a circular stone layering within the dependent portion of the gallbladder (arrow). There is no gallbladder wall thickening or pericholecystic edema.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig15">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig16.jpeg" height="745" width="834" aria-labelledby="fig16" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16</span> Primary sclerosing cholangitis. Axial CT enterographic image in a patient with Crohn disease shows a heterogeneous enhancement pattern and an abnormally dilated bile duct within segment VII of the liver (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig16">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.337105140/asset/images/large/rg.337105140.fig17.jpeg" height="758" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig17" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17</span> Vascular thrombosis. Axial CT enterographic image of the liver in a patient with Crohn disease shows a filling defect within the right hepatic vein (arrow). The liver peripheral to the thrombosed hepatic vein has a heterogeneous attenuation pattern.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.337105140&amp;id=fig17">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Kim SC, Ferry GD. Inflammatory bowel diseases in pediatric and adolescent patients: clinical, therapeutic, and psychosocial considerations. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2004;126(6):1550–1560.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2004.03.022">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15168366/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Inflammatory+bowel+diseases+in+pediatric+and+adolescent+patients%3A+clinical%2C+therapeutic%2C+and+psychosocial+considerations&amp;author=SC+Kim&amp;author=GD+Ferry&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Gastroenterology&amp;pages=1550-1560&amp;doi=10.1053%2Fj.gastro.2004.03.022&amp;pmid=15168366">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div clas